{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 23:18:29.319752", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nScope and checks performed\\n- End-to-end IP reachability across the topology (multi-host ping matrix)\\n- Point tests from two representative user hosts (host_1_1_1_1 in 10.1.1.0/24 and host_2_1_1_1 in 10.2.1.0/24) to server-farm components (DNS, load balancer, and web servers)\\n- DNS resolution timing as seen by curl\\n- HTTP transaction timing (name lookup, connect, TTFB, total) to web99.local (load balancer) and to web0–web3 both by FQDN and direct IPs\\n\\nKey observations\\n1) Underlay and routing health\\n- Multi-host reachability: 0% packet loss across tested pairs; typical RTTs 1.5–4 ms. Example from matrix: dhcp_server→10.1.2.15 avg 3.86 ms, dns_server→10.2.2.18 avg 3.92 ms, numerous host↔host tests all 0% loss with low RTT.\\n- From user hosts:\\n  - ICMP to DNS (10.200.0.2), LB (10.200.0.7), and each web_server_0–3 (10.200.0.3–.6) succeeds with low RTT (~2–4 ms).\\n  - TCP connect latency to HTTP endpoints is consistently low (connect ~2–12 ms).\\n- OSPF reachability of 10.200.0.0/24 appears correct; no evidence of asymmetric routing or loss.\\n\\nAssessment: IP connectivity, switching, and OSPF routing are healthy.\\n\\n2) DNS health\\n- Curl name lookup times are consistently low (~3–10 ms) from both user hosts, indicating DNS service responsiveness and low DNS path latency.\\n- Slow HTTP transactions persist even when accessing servers by IP, ruling out DNS as a cause of application slowness.\\n\\nAssessment: DNS is healthy and not a bottleneck.\\n\\n3) HTTP service behavior\\n- Load balancer (web99.local, 10.200.0.7):\\n  - From host_1_1_1_1: TTFB ~0.246–0.324 s; total ~1.05–1.12 s.\\n  - From host_2_1_1_1: TTFB ~0.196–0.241 s; total ~1.00–1.05 s.\\n  - Stable, low-latency responses.\\n- Direct web servers (web0–web3; 10.200.0.3–.6):\\n  - Frequent elevated TTFB ~3.1–4.1 s with totals ~4.0–4.7 s.\\n  - Occasional fast responses (e.g., some runs ~0.29–0.43 s TTFB, ~1.1–2.2 s total), but majority are slow.\\n  - This slowness occurs when accessed by FQDN and by direct IP, and from both user subnets, with consistently low TCP connect times.\\n\\nRepresentative samples\\n- host_1_1_1_1 → web0.local: TTFB 3.43–3.73 s; total 4.24–4.54 s.\\n- host_1_1_1_1 → 10.200.0.3: TTFB 2.33–3.89 s; total 3.13–4.69 s.\\n- host_1_1_1_1 → web1.local/.4/.5/.6: same pattern—many runs with TTFB ~3.1–4.1 s.\\n- host_2_1_1_1 → web0.local and 10.200.0.3: mixed, often TTFB ~3.6–3.9 s with occasional fast run.\\n\\nAssessment: The HTTP delay is within the server-side processing window (TTFB), not in network setup or DNS.\\n\\nDetected anomalies\\n- Abnormal application-layer latency specifically on the Apache web servers (web_server_0–web_server_3):\\n  - High and variable TTFB (~3–4 s) from multiple clients/subnets and using both DNS and IP.\\n  - Network path indicators (ICMP RTT, TCP connect) are normal during these delays.\\n- Load balancer service (web99.local) does not exhibit this latency, suggesting its backends (separate from web0–web3) are healthy and that the server access path is not the bottleneck.\\n\\nFault localization\\n- Affected devices: web_server_0 (10.200.0.3), web_server_1 (10.200.0.4), web_server_2 (10.200.0.5), web_server_3 (10.200.0.6).\\n- Unaffected devices: dns_server (10.200.0.2), load_balancer (10.200.0.7), routers/switches in the data path.\\n- Network segments and OSPF domain: no evidence of faults.\\n\\nRoot cause analysis\\n- The consistent pattern of low ICMP RTT, low TCP connect time, fast DNS, and delayed time-to-first-byte points to server-side application latency on the Apache servers, not a transport/routing issue.\\n- The magnitude (~3–4 s) and variability are characteristic of application or server configuration problems (e.g., blocking operations before response, reverse DNS lookups during request processing/logging, or other server-side delays). While the precise application misconfiguration is not confirmed here, the root cause domain is the HTTP server stack on web0–web3.\\n\\nOverall network health verdict\\n- Underlay network, OSPF routing, and DNS: normal.\\n- Server farm access path and load balancer: normal.\\n- Service anomaly: degraded performance on Apache web servers web0–web3 due to server-side processing delays., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='4183880b-9a3b-4f61-bd47-eaa02ec680dd'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
